When I heard the sand at the beach was red, my first thought was ‘hmm, not sure I’ll enjoy painting that’😆 As it happens, the sands hues became my teacher (when aren’t we learning??) on our trip to Nova Scotia.
The play of light took the beach through a myriad of tones throughout the day, from fresh salmon to deepest chocolate browns with cooler tones of lilac and mauve in between. A challenge for a painter no doubt😅 but an unexpected delight as well. Join me for this episode of Art in bloom as we move through the hues of a Canadian beach in Summer. #canada#novascotia#magnolianetwork#discoveryplus#beachpainting#letspaint#goauchelandscape#landscapepainting

The process of painting my Pansy pieces. This collection began in 2017 as a way to meditate. I wanted to be able to ‘zone out’ whilst becoming familiar with my subject matter, which is how they ended up in simple rows. Each Pansy became a character and painting them in a grid format allowed me to concentrate on them as individuals. They soon became a whole without me noticing, although I did make sure each individual felt ‘friendly’ to its neighbor with just a couple of awkward guys to keep balance😄 This big (24”x30”) piece is now available as a limited edition print🤗🤗🤗#pansies#happyfaces#watercolorflorals#paintingprocess#pansy#handpainteddesign#interiordesign#patternpla#doitfortheprocess

Petal by petal. For these new Pansy paintings I’m layering up inks and watercolors from the tube over many hours. Often I’ll work on several at a time so I can do the dance of drying time. 

I mix areas of wet on wet with areas painted on dry paper, then often come in with washes on top of those layers once they are dry or in a state of dampness. 

The waltz between what to add and when just comes with time, practice and knowing how ‘soft’ I want an area to be or how defined. 

I’m using Indian inks, some diluted some straight, watercolors from the tube from various brands. A 1” filbert for washes, a size 14 round and smally round for details😊
This collection will be available Feb 2nd! Sign up to my mailing list before Jan 29th( link in stories) to see a preview💫

Pushing through the discomfort and experimenting is where we learn. Sometimes I have a painting that is perfectly fine but I know I’ll only grow if I challenge myself to push it that bit further. Here’s an example of layering up inks. There was a point I almost popped it under the table and walked away but a few more layers and some deep breaths got me to a more interesting and dynamic piece/peace😅 #roses #watercolorflorals #watercolorartist #artistsofinstagram #doitfortheprocess

Foxgloves. Lots of layering again on this one. I’m experimenting with a matte glaze over inks and then I’m going to try painting in acrylic or gouache on top. We shall see what happens folks! Anyone tried this type of layering on paper before? I’d love to hear what you’ve learnt from layering your mediums, drop a line in the comments! #foxgloves #mixedmediaart #carveouttimeforart #doitfortheprocess #floralpaintings

Pisces season at the studio. I’m taking time to focus on oil painting, something I’ve had a real hang up about. Well, I decided to rip the band aid off and create a whopper based on an initial study from a few years back. Many layers to go on this piece. It’s been humbling and exciting in equal parts working in a new medium. I can find 4 hours goes by without me noticing ( magic time). I can also spend 4 hours on one tiny portion without success 😬 On we go! Thank you for tips and tricks to oils from my stories the other day, I’ve taken them all in and already deployed a few😃💫

Morning charcoal sketching at camp. The sun is strong and the bugs are bugging but I’m enjoying 15 minute sketches around the camp in Colorado. Easy to pack a tinted pad and a black and white charcoal, and to keep a nicely limited palette. Using hairspray to set thaw charcoal before turning to a new piece of paper. #colorado #steamboatsprings #sketchingnature
Sketching by the creek with charcoal pencils. #drawingoftheday #drawingsketch

1. For smaller pieces of art charcoal pencils are great. The pencil has a coating you sharpen off and this keeps your hands pretty clean. 

2. When possible work from the top of the paper down to avoid smudging.

3. Get a putty eraser for any rogue smudges.

4. Tinted paper is great for adding depth to a piece. Having a mid-tone paper as a base allows the use of other colored pastels like tan and white to build up a more detailed drawing.

5. You don’t need fancy fixative sprays to fix the charcoal. Hairspray works very well. You can even spray between layers so if you need to go back to it later give it a light spray and you should be able to work on top again ( always test this on a test strip of paper before trying on a larger piece of art though 😉).

6. A set of charcoal pencils are a nice, compact way to create when traveling! #charcoalart #drawingoftheday #colorado #drawingwithcharcoal

Stretch your paper onto a table or board.
Layer 1: Mask out flowers in the background and paint deep color of your choice using ink. Wait for that layer to dry and take off the masking fluid. Paint into the flowers in the background. Let that layer dry completely.
Layer 2: using a sponge brush, wet the entire painting, (there will be some smudging of darker inks in first layer)then add in another color on top I used rust water based ink. This new layer darkens the original florals so that all the imagery recedes quite a lot. When the ink is almost dry spray with a water bottle to create a speckled texture. Allow this layer to dry.

Layer 3: once your background is completely dry, begin painting in your top layer flowers using gouache or acrylic, lots of time taken on this final layer as it’s the focal flower. Allow to dry and admire your work!

It’s that time of the year. Been pondering a lot lately, and I bet you’ve had your share of introspection too. I hope you’re all doing ok. 
This space has always been a place I hope to bring inspiration and levity, so let’s talk art – creating it, soaking in it, being part of it. It’s been my haven, my escape. Sometimes, I’ve taken for granted the museums, art, and materials at my fingertips – the luck of where I’m from and my privilege. As we come to a close on 2023 I’m feeling an immense gratitude surge. 
As we roll into 2024, here’s to all of us finding solace, connection, and peace in our creative journeys. It’s never been more important to share and appreciate where we find joy. Much love to each and every one of you, always. - H
